971
972 // Currently there are two syntaxes (old and new, respectively) for INSERT
973 // .. VALUES statements:
974 //
975 // - INSERT .. VALUES (), () ..
976 // - INSERT .. VALUES ROW(), ROW() ..
977 //
978 // The latter is a table value constructor, i.e. it has an subquery
979 // expression, while the former is the standard VALUES syntax. When the
980 // non-standard VALUES() function (primarily used in ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE
981 // update expressions) is deprecated in the future, the old syntax can be used
982 // as a table value constructor as well.
983 //
984 // However, until such a change is made, we convert INSERT statements with
985 // table value constructors into PT_insert objects that are equal to the old
986 // syntax, as to enforce consistency by making sure they both follow the same
987 // execution path.
988 //
989 // Note that this removes the constness of both row_value_list and
990 // insert_query_expression, which should both be restored when deprecating
991 // VALUES as mentioned above.
